          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>New York 144 Thompson St</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="aling(right)">
                                        <date>March 21<hi rend="sup">st</hi> 5613. 1853</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>Dear Sir/</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">The sealed enclosure addressed to you<lb/> my
                                        Brother brought from <placeName>California</placeName>
                                        and<lb/> the German paper is an extract from a<lb/> Letter
                                        recd by a resident of <placeName>New York</placeName><lb/>
                                        it was given to me by a very respectable<lb/> and truthful
                                        man who wishes you to translate<lb/> and insert it the
                                        “Occident” I believe<lb/> there is much truth in what is
                                        said<lb/> concerning the <add>Hebrew</add> but of course
                                        you<lb/> will exercise your own discretion—<lb/> wishing you
                                        every happiness you yourself<lb/> desire  I am yours
                                        faithfully</p>
                              <p>
                                        <persName role="author">Ansel Leo</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>To</p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <placeName>371—Walnut St</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <add>?</add>
                                        <persName>Adolph Back</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <placeName>275 William st:</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">
                                        <placeName>N. Y.</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <add>
                                                  <hi rend="underline">Yiddish</hi>
                                        </add>
                              </p>
                              <p>copy</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">My dear friend <persName>Herr Bach</persName>,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Large orders for Tifillin and Mazuzot<lb/> come
                                        over from there*, and people send out such as are<lb/> for
                                        the most part improper. The leather for the<lb/> thongs of
                                        the T'fillin is bought here form such<lb/> animals which are
                                        forbidden in the Torah. In<lb/> the same way, they make the
                                        cases for the T'fillin<lb/> for head and arm in an improper
                                        manner. Much<lb/> less can the Parashoth contained in them
                                        be<lb/> Kosher since the scribe has them printed and<lb/>
                                        sells a complete pair of T'fillin for 6 or 6 ½<lb/> groshen.
                                        Therefore, I think it would be a great<lb/> “Mitzva” to have
                                        it announced there among the<lb/> pious and whole hearted
                                        that whatever T'fillin and<lb/> Mezuzot arrive there,
                                        without the seal of a legi-<lb/>timate court, should not be
                                        accepted as Kosher,<lb/> and that a legitimate court will
                                        take care that<lb/> T'fillin and Mezuzot as well as Torahs
                                        should be sent<lb/> out in a Kosher fashion.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Your friend who blesses you and<lb/> your house
                                        with all good</p>
                              <p rend="indent(6)">
                                        <persName role="author">David Schlesinger</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(6)">Dayyau of <placeName>Breslau</placeName></p>
                              <p>*<placeName>America</placeName>, presumably</p>
                              <p>“Judge”</p>
                    </body>
